# identi???es exemplars among data points and forms clusters of data points around these exemplars
# operates by simultaneously considering all data point as potential exemplars and exchanging messages between data points until a good set of exemplars and clusters emerges
#takes similarity matrix from LSA

cluster <- function(i, clusters, pagerank, n=10){
  group <- clusters$names[clusters$membership == i]
  pagerank[group, ] %>% sort(decreasing = TRUE) %>% head(n)
}

Including Plots

You can also embed plots, for example:

plot(wc,g.1a, layout=layout1)

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.

#https://www.r-bloggers.com/network-visualization-in-r-with-the-igraph-package/
#subset on basis of degree
redung.1a<-V(g.1a)[degree(g.1a)<4]

#identify those vertices part of less than three edges
subg.1a<-delete.vertices(g.1a, redung.1a) #exclude them from the graph

wc_subg.1a<-walktrap.community(subg.1a)
wc_subg.1a
## IGRAPH clustering walktrap, groups: 20, mod: 0.3
## + groups:

##    [1] "inflammation"    "atherosclerosis" "estrogen"

##   + ... omitted several groups/vertices
plot(wc_subg.1a, subg.1a, layout=layout1)
